    {
      "title": "Update Kanban board for automatic completion date tracking",
      "description": "Backfill completedAt timestamps on existing done cards. The DB API now stamps completedAt when cards move to done, but the 23 existing done cards lack this field. Write a one-time script or API call to set completedAt = updatedAt for all done cards missing it, so the daily summary can pick them up historically.\n\n---\n**Auto-executed by Task Executor** (2026-03-12 02:20)\nBuild succeeds. Here's the summary:\n\n---\n\n**Done — backfilled `completedAt` on all 23 done cards.**\n\nAll 23 cards in the \"done\" column were missing the `completedAt` timestamp. I set `completedAt = updatedAt` for each one directly in `lib/db.json`. The MC build passes clean.\n\n**Why this matters:** The daily summary feature (`/api/daily-summary`) uses `completedAt` to figure out which tasks were completed on a given day. Without it, those 23 historical cards were invisible to the summary. Now they'll show up correctly when looking back at past days.\n\n**One thing to note:** All 23 cards had the same `updatedAt` value (`1773118753782` — March 7, 2026), likely from a bulk migration or schema update. So they'll all appear as completed on that same date in the daily summary. That's the best we can do without original completion dates, but going forward, new cards moved to \"done\" get a real-time `completedAt` stamp automatically.\n\nNo new files, cron jobs, or MC pages needed — this was a one-time data fix.",
      "labels": [
        "Mission-Control",
        "Daily-Summary"
      ],
      "priority": "Med",
      "column": "done",
      "order": 17,
      "_id": "card_1773248144002",
      "createdAt": 1773248144002,
      "updatedAt": 1773351517341,
      "executorStatus": "completed",
      "completedAt": 1773280780987
    },
    {
      "_id": "card_1773249585233",
      "title": "[Research & Install] Paperclip AI — Smart Clipboard Manager",
      "description": "Research https://github.com/paperclipai/paperclip and decide if we should install it.\n\nSTEPS:\n1. Go to the GitHub repo, read the README, understand what it does and how it works\n2. Evaluate: Is this useful for our AI operating system? How would it integrate?\n3. Run Guard Dog security scan on the package BEFORE installing\n4. If Guard Dog approves and it looks valuable, install it\n5. Create a Mission Control page for it with relevant dashboard/controls\n6. Integrate it into the OpenClaw AI operating system in the best way possible\n7. Register in agent registry if applicable\n\nCONTEXT:\n- This is Joe's AI copilot system running on Mac mini M2\n- All new tools should integrate with the existing agent ecosystem\n- Follow the 3-phase MC build rule: Build → Test (npm run build) → Polish\n- Guard Dog pre-install scan is mandatory for all new packages\n\n---\n**Task Executor Failed** (2026-03-12 04:27, exit: 1)\nTask timed out after 2 hours\n\n---\n**Auto-executed by Task Executor** (2026-03-12 12:08)\nch. Here's the situation:\n\n---\n\n**Paperclip AI — Research Complete, Recommending SKIP**\n\nThe task card described Paperclip as a \"Smart Clipboard Manager\" — that's incorrect. **Paperclip is actually an open-source AI agent orchestration platform** (19K GitHub stars, MIT license, created March 2 — only 10 days old). It's a full Node.js server + React UI + PostgreSQL database that manages teams of AI agents with org charts, budgets, governance, and heartbeats.\n\n**Guard Dog scan**: Passed (SAFE, 65% confidence). No CVEs, no malicious patterns.\n\n**Why I'm recommending against installing:**\n\n1. **Massive overlap with your existing system.** You already have Mission Control (dashboard), agent-registry.json (org chart), task-executor (task processing), and Scrooge (cost tracking). Paperclip would be a second, competing orchestration layer.\n\n2. **It's a full standalone application**, not a library. It needs PostgreSQL, pnpm, runs its own server on port 3100, and has its own React UI. This isn't something you \"install\" — it's something you migrate to.\n\n3. **It's 10 days old.** Despite 19K stars, it was created March 2. Too early to bet infrastructure on.\n\n4. **Your current system is better tailored to your needs.** You have direct Slack/Telegram/WhatsApp integration, custom agents, MC pages — Paperclip would require rebuilding all of that within its framework.\n\n**What IS worth stealing from Paperclip's design:**\n- Per-agent budget enforcement (your Scrooge agent could evolve here)\n- Heartbeat-based scheduling (you partially have this with launchd)\n- Goal ancestry on tasks (tasks carrying the \"why\" from company mission down)\n\nThese concepts could be added to Mission Control incrementally without adopting the whole platform.\n\n**Bottom line:** Paperclip solves the exact problem you've already solved with Mission Control + agents + task executor. It's interesting to watch, but installing it now would add complexity without clear value. Revisit in 3-6 months when it's more mature.",
      "labels": [
        "research",
        "integration",
        "guard-dog"
      ],
      "priority": "Med",
      "column": "review",
      "order": 4,
      "createdAt": 1773249585233,
      "updatedAt": 1773352388579,
      "executorStatus": "completed"
    },
    {
      "title": "Install this https://clawhub.ai/maximeprades/auto-updater",
      "description": "\n\n---\n**Auto-executed by Task Executor** (2026-03-12 02:12)\nDone. Here's what happened:\n\n**Installed the `auto-updater` skill from ClawHub** (`clawhub install auto-updater`) — it's now at `/Users/openclaw/skills/auto-updater/`.\n\n**Created the daily auto-update script** at `~/.openclaw/workspace/ops/auto-updater.sh` that:\n- Runs `clawhub update --all` to update every installed ClawHub skill\n- Checks the current OpenClaw version\n- Lists all installed skill versions\n- Outputs a formatted summary\n\n**Registered a cron job** in `~/.openclaw/cron/jobs.json` — runs daily at **4:30 AM SGT** (shifted from 4 AM to avoid conflicting with Emmie's inbox review). It delivers the update summary to Telegram.\n\n**Test run worked** and actually updated the `canva` skill to 1.0.0 during the test.\n\n**Heads up — two flags from the test run:**\n1. **`evolver` skill is flagged as malicious** by ClawHub's VirusTotal scan and is blocked from updating\n2. **`feishu-evolver-wrapper` is flagged as suspicious** — skipped unless you force it\n\nThese were pre-existing installs, not related to the auto-updater. You may want to investigate or uninstall them if you don't need them.\n\nNo MC dashboard page needed for this — it's a simple daily cron that reports via Telegram. You'll see the update summaries in your Telegram each morning and the job shows up on your Mission Control Calendar.",
      "labels": [],
      "priority": "Low",
      "dueDate": "",
